    Peer-graded Assignment: Plotting data and fitting a curve

    DeadlineApr 22, 8:59 AM CEST
    Ready for the assignment?
    You will find instructions below to submit.

    Coursera Lab Sandbox

    Beta

    • Easily launch Coursera's preconfigured environment for Julia

    • Get access to all dependencies (libraries and packages) for Jupyter Notebook—no local software installation required

    • Practice Julia, run test cases, and work on assignments from your browser

    1. Instructions
    2. My submission
    3. Discussions

    Imagine a scenario similar to the steps involved in fitting the SIR model to actual Ebola data. For this assignment we provide data that should be fitted a parabola. You will be asked to plot the data and adjust the coefficients of simple curve to give an approximate fit. The purpose here is to use a Jupyter Notebook to show all the step involved in an analysis. The exact fit is less important; rather it should be clear that each step can be reproduced and the thinking followed.

    Week3_PR_Template
    ZIP File

    Download the 'Week3_PR_Template.zip', a zip file with a starter Notebooks for this assignment, by clicking the button above. Or alternatively you may wish to create a new Notebook. To work with a Notebook you can use IJulia (requires a local installation: installation guide). A Jupyter Notebook template is available or you can create your own notebook. If you are creating a new Notebook there is a drop-down menu called 'new' on the right of the screen when opening. Select a Julia notebook from the list of options. (There may be several versions listed. Avoid the older versions, although all the listed versions are likely to work for this assignment.) For each step below create a cell and write code to produce the required output. The toolbar button '+' creates new cells.

    1. In the Notebooks ensure the first cell is of type 'Markdown'. If you need to change the cell type, select the 'Cell Type' option from the Cell menu, then choose 'Markdown'. The cell type drop-down menu on the toolbar also allows you to change between the 'Code' and 'Markdown' cell type. Now type in a title in the cell. The title should be descriptive. The convention is to use the markdown format: starting with '#' such as: # Week 3 - Fitting a curve

    2. Create a new code cell below that will load the data into an array called data_tofitdata\_tofitdata_tofit. This array is already defined in the Week3_PR_Template.ipynb also in 'Week3_PR_Template.zip'. The additionally includes 'Week3_PR_Data.dat' that can be read in directly.

    3. Create a new code cell below. Write a ‘For’ loop to print out all the values of data_tofitdata\_tofitdata_tofit. The result should be numbers in 15 rows and two columns.

    4. Create a new code cell below. Assign the values from the first column of data_tofitdata\_tofitdata_tofit into a new array called xxx. Similarly assign the values from the second column of data_tofitdata\_tofitdata_tofit into a new array called yyy.

    5. Create a new code cell below. Create a scatter plot with the x- and y-values on the x-axis and y-axis respectively.

    6. Create a new code cell below. Create a function called parabfitparabfitparabfit, with a single parameter xxx , that returns the value of the expression ax2+bx+cax^2 + bx + cax2+bx+c for a given xxx. The values for the variables aaa, bbb, and ccc will be defined next. Execute the code to create your function.

    7. Create a new code cell below. Assign the value 1 to the variables aaa, bbb, and ccc respectively. Now create a plot of the curve defined by the parabfitparabfitparabfit function using: plot(parabfit,−5,5)plot(parabfit, -5, 5)plot(parabfit,−5,5)

    At this point you have created all the basic components needed. You will have noticed that the data points in the scatter plot and the shape of the curve are quite different. Notebooks are useful to document that steps to getting a curve that more closely fits. While there are mathematical techniques for fitting curves, such solutions are not always be appropriate for describing the steps for getting an approximate fit to a simple function.

    1. Create a new code cell. In this cell assign new values to aaa, bbb, and ccc to fit the dat (hint: you can tell whether a is positive or negative, and you can guess at the value of c. In fact also b, which is the slope at x=0). Then copy the plot()plot()plot() statement from above to display the scatter plot of the data and finally plot!()plot!()plot!() to overlay the function curve.

    2. Re-execute the above cell changing the values of aaa, bbb, and ccc. By changing the sign or size of these variables can flip or shift the parabola’s position. Note that by looking at where the data points lie, we can deduce some of the properties for aaa, bbb, and ccc, as follows. The plot must have a y-intersection that is close to 0, so ccc is close to 0. Also, the parabola is open downwards, so aaa must be negative. Finally, it has its maximum at a positive x, so bbb must be positive. You will not need to consider values outside the range −4-4−4 and 444. It is often useful to include comments as your tried to identify reasonable fits (use # at the start). Each time regenerate the plot of the data and parabola. In the plots reduce the range for xxx to positive values (e,g, 0 to 6) to more clearly view the fitted line. When you're happy with the fit, make sure you've given the diagram an informative title (you need not annotate the axes, as they are just numbers).

    3. Create a new Markdown cell below. Add comments about reaching the parameters you chose. For example you might describe your process as follows: "Initially the values for a, b and c were not very good, a and b were too small, though c seemed good. Finally adjusting these further produced a parabola with a good approximation of the data.."

    Ensure you have run each cell in your Notebook. Now save your Jupyter Notebook to a file on your local computer. With your Notebook open, select 'Download as' from the File menu. We recommend using HTML (not executable). Give your Notebook an appropriate name such as: ‘Week3_Fit’. The file must be easy for anyone else to open and review. While you could share your IPython Notebook, allowing a reviewer to run the code, rather avoid file formats that other people may not expect or be familiar with opening.

    Finally upload your saved Jupyter Notebook file below for peer review. While you can delete your submission and upload a revised Notebook, you may lose reviews submitted by peers and have to wait a little longer.

    If you want to share your submitted assignment in the discussion forum for grading, make use of this link to create a shareable assignment link which lets you share your submission in the forums as a link.

    A peer will be asked to check that you have done the following steps:

    • Has a Jupyter Notebook (as an HTML file) been submitted?

    • Does the Notebook have a title or heading?

    • Is a scatter plot for x and y produced?

    • Is a plot of the parabfit function produced?

    • Are new values for a, b and c estimated? A close to -0.8, close to 3 and c approximately -2.

    • Is a single plot, showing both the scatter plot and fitted parabola plot, produced?
